John Edward: Essential Language Skills for Global Citizens
Private schools in Scotland hold record for academic excellence and this has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, further reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other fields.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the highest level of service to their pupils and parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further higher-level education, for their chosen careers and their country as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailored educational curriculum, we are demonstrating how modern-language skills continue to be a widespread and popular choice across schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to someone in a language that he understands, your words go to their ears.
If you speak to him in your own language, your words go to your heart.”
These words are a powerful reminder that we can't rely only on English when we want to build relationships with people from foreign countries.
From the results of this year's final exams, we can find that languages are leading the list of results, with the highest rate of passing grades among private schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who have studied foreign languages have received the maximum score A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of the students had received the maximum A score in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied Spanish, and 63 percent of those who studied French.
This shows that private schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as one of the vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, foreign language proficiency is considered as important as STEM branches (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of private schools.
A 2014 study by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that among the main difficulties employers faced in filling vacancies, 17 per cent of them were linked to a lack of linguistic skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming more and more necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With the addition of jobs that are subject to the mastery of foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career you choose a person, if he has learned a second language, he will have real advantages in the future, as the master of such a long-term ability.
The ability to communicate directly with foreign people will automatically position a multilingual person over their competitors.
According to a survey by YouGov, which included more than 4,000 adults from the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to develop a conversation, and French was the only one with a specific 15-speech language.
That's why investing in language learning is important for today's children.
The mastery of many languages, in particular the mastery of languages of developing countries, will give children a better chance of employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught in them.
Some schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will offer languages considered the most important to the UK in the 2020 outlook, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a range of languages from which you can choose in private schools, with pedagogical staff composed of specialists in the field.
Scottish private schools are dedicated to providing a school environment that will prepare children and "arm" them with the skills they need to carry out, whatever the future.
In these times it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to play a vital role in the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should truly be regarded as "the ability to communicate internationally."
Private schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Board of Private Schools.
