A new course at Harvard University this year has involved all students to sleep more, in an effort to fight the growing culture of ‘mass’ of study through the use of caffeine from these ‘sleepless’.
One academic noted that university students number one in the world often don't know when it comes to the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women's Hospital, prepared the lessons course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start this course after giving a reference to the impact that sleep has on learning.
"At the end of the day, a girl approached me and said, 'Why is this being said to me now, in my last year?'
She said no one had spoken to her before about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, included in the program for the first time this year, explains to students the essential elements of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's general director of medical services, said the university decided to present this course after finding that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The course that lasts an hour involves a number of interactive tasks.
On the one hand, there is a view of a comfortable room, where students click on the cups of coffee, curtains, athletes and books so that they can explain the effects of caffeine and lighting and how the athletic performance is affected by the lack of sleep, as well as the weight of the bed.
On the other hand, participants were explained how deprivation of sleep over a long period increases the risk of heart attack, ischaemia, depression, and cancer.
A camp map, with an interactive icon, further encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - as you have a right to know, the health impact when you choose to smoke," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride to spend “a night without sleep” continues to exist, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that deprivation of sleep was an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring that you have taken the adequate dose of sleep, of a good quality, should be the students’ ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said – even to avoid weight gain, because deprivation of sleep leads to hunger and hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course after attending one of his lesson hours last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and had inspired him to turn it into a course for the whole camp.
He hopes that the next step, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining competing institutions.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should set an hour of sleep when they need to go to bed, and also that when they need to wake up, be aware of the harmful effects of ‘blue light’ coming out of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can bring problems to the brain.
